How to Download Financial Statements Data from the Internet#

Sources of Financial Statements on the Internet#

Source: Company Website#

The financial statements of a company are typically found in the annual reports which are published on its website. This is a primary source of financial statements.

SEC Filings#

In the United States, publicly listed companies are required by law to submit filings regularly to the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC). The common filings are:

  • Form 10-K: provide comprehensive and detailed information about a companys financial performance, operations, and risks to the SEC and the public, ensuring transparency, regulatory compliance, and informed decision-making for investors and stakeholders.

  • Form 10-Q: provide timely and condensed financial updates on a quarterly basis to the SEC and the public, facilitating ongoing assessment of a companys performance and financial condition.

  • Form 8-K: promptly disclose significant corporate events or changes that may impact investors decisions, ensuring transparency and timely dissemination of material information to the SEC and the public.

  • proxy statement: provide shareholders with information about matters to be voted on at a companys annual meeting, including executive compensation, corporate governance, and shareholder proposals, enabling informed voting decisions and promoting transparency in corporate governance.

  • Forms 3,4, and 5: report insider transactions (such as buying or selling company stock) by corporate insiders, including officers, directors, and beneficial owners, to the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC), ensuring transparency and compliance with regulatory requirements regarding insider trading.

  • Schedule 13: disclose significant ownership stakes or changes in ownership positions in publicly traded companies by institutional investors or other entities, providing transparency and regulatory compliance to the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) and the public.

  • Form 114: also known as the Foreign Bank Account Report (FBAR), is to report foreign financial accounts held by United States persons or entities to the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN), ensuring compliance with anti-money laundering regulations and promoting transparency in international financial transactions.

  • Foreign Investment Disclosures

The financial statements are found in 10-K (annually) and 8-K (quarterly).

Source: EDGAR#

Electronic Data Gathering, Analysis, and Retrieval (EDGAR) is the electronic filing system created by the SEC to increase the efficiency and accessibility of corporate filings. The system is used by all publicly traded companies when submitting required documents to the SEC.

This is another source of company financial statements.

10-K for KO#

Part II Item 8#

The financial statements and accompanying notes are found under Part II Item 8:

Understanding the URL#

In the URL https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/21344/000002134424000009/ko-20231231.htm,

  • 21344: Central Index Key or CIK number (EDGAR assigns to filers a unique numerical identifier)

  • 000002134424000009: accession number (unique identifier assigned automatically to an accepted submission by EDGAR)

  • KO: ticker symbol

  • 20231231: YYYYMMDD

Such information and others on how EDGAR data may be accessed may be found here: https://www.sec.gov/os/accessing-edgar-data

EDGAR API#

EDGAR may also be accessed programmatically through its Application Programming Interfaces (API). This allows financial statement data to be accessed through code written in various programming languages. The API is organized as follows:

  • submission: contains metadata such as current name, former name, and stock exchanges and ticker symbols

  • company-concept: disclosures from a single company (CIK) and concept (a taxonomy and tag)

  • company-facts: all the company concepts data for a company in a single API call

  • frames: aggregates one fact for each reporting entity that is last filed that most closely fits the calendrical period requested

Information on EDGARs API may be found here: https://www.sec.gov/edgar/sec-api-documentation

Using Python Packages#

API Access#

We will not directly read from the EDGAR API. Instead, we will make use of the following open-source Python packages for this:

  • EDGAR Tools

    • GitHub: https://dgunning.github.io/edgartools/

    • PyPI: https://pypi.org/project/edgartools/

As this package connects directly to the EDGAR API, the downloading is limited by the constraints set on the SEC database servers.

An alternative to EDGAR Tools is sec-edgar-api found at https://sec-edgar-api.readthedocs.io/en/latest/, or secfsdstools found at https://pypi.org/project/secfsdstools/.

We will also make use of the following packages by Jeroen Bouma which are useful for financial analysis:

  • Finance Database

    • Home: https://www.jeroenbouma.com/projects/financetoolkit

    • GitHub: JerBouma/FinanceToolkit

    • PyPI: https://pypi.org/project/financedatabase/

  • Finance Toolkit

    • Home: https://www.jeroenbouma.com/projects/financetoolkit

    • GitHub: JerBouma/FinanceDatabase

    • PyPI: https://pypi.org/project/financetoolkit/

While the packages financedatabase and financetoolkit are open source, the data source is FinancialModelingPrep, which isnt free.

To use these packages, you will need to register at: https://site.financialmodelingprep.com/sign-up

and obtain an API key from your dashboard: https://site.financialmodelingprep.com/developer/docs/dashboard

The Free plan is limited to 250 requests each day, 5 years of data and only features companies listed on US exchanges.

Installation#

Lets install these package on our system.

This can be done directly in a Jupyter Notebook, like this:

# Installation on Jupyter Notebook

!pip install edgartools
!pip install financedatabase -U
!pip install financetoolkit -U

or on the command line/command prompt/console/terminal (using the same commmands, but replacing !pip with pip).

Testing the Packages#

Once installed, the packages may be immediately tested for their presence by importing 

# Testing the Packages in Python

from edgar import *
import financedatabase as fd
from financetoolkit import Toolkit

Comparing Balance Sheets#

Lets quickly try out EDGAR Tools and Finance Toolkit for their abilities to produce the balance sheet, against the standard found on EDGAR.

Finance Database is useful when one wishes to inspect and query high-level aspects of companies, such as the industry a company belongs to, the exchanges on which it trades, etc.. So, we wont use it to search for balance sheet data.

Recall that EDGAR Tools is a Python package that facilitates accessing data from EDGAR. Its data source is EDGAR. It has some helper functions to make life easier for the user. On the other hand, what distinguishes Finance Toolkit as a Python package is that it comes with many functions that support the financial analysis of companies. Its data source is FinancialModelingPrep.

#
# Let's first use EDGAR Tools to access KO's balance sheet.
#

# The first step in using EDGAR Tools
from edgar import *

# Tell the SEC who you are - the following name comes from PyPI
set_identity("Michael Mccallum mike.mccalum@indigo.com")

# Set the company of interest
company = Company("KO")

# The (latest) balance sheet may be viewed this way
bs = company.financials.balance_sheet

Balance Sheet from EDGAR#


Note that Short-Term Investments as a field is populated with values on the balance sheet found on EDGAR:






Reliability and Attribution#


When a characteristic of a company, such as its Short Term Investments, is given to you, with a value, one important question to ask is: Who says so?


This concerns the reliability of the data.


When data is obtained from EDGAR, we trust that it is reliable because we know that all companies must submit their audited financial statements to SEC through EDGAR. When we use data from EDGAR and attribute the source to EDGAR, it firms up the arguments that we make in a financial analysis of a company.


In the finance industry, the most reliable sources of data are:


    

  • primary sources (i.e. data producers)
    • 

  • regulator repository
    • 

  • Bloomberg, LSEG Workspace, Factset, etc.
    • 



As we can see, the data from FinancialModelingPrep seems identical to the data from EDGAR. (If the output is too large, scroll right with the mouse to see the hidden side of the data table.)


This gives us some faith in using the data for financial analysis. This is fine as long as the analysis is meant for private consumption. When it is meant for use by others, such as in the report of a financial analyst, then appropriate attribution is crucial as it affects the trustworthiness of the report.


The balance sheet output from EDGAR Tools isnt incorrect. It is missing data. This output is a convenience functionality of the package unrelated to the EDGAR access functionality.








Collating EDGAR Data into a Balance Sheet#




EDGAR as Source#


As EDGAR is the most important source for financial statements, we will illustrate the steps in extracting the balance sheet from EDGAR in this section.

# The output shows that EDGAR stores, in addition to company filings,

#
df = company.get_facts().to_pandas()

Searching for a Fact on EDGAR#


Lets see if we can find Short-Term Investments in the fact column.


To ease our search, we will filter for all facts that contain the string investments in the lower case.


As we should realize from this, one challenge in using data from EDGAR is figuring out how fields on financial statements are encoded as facts in EDGAR.






# Let's first filter out facts from 10-K FY2023.
# This reduces the number of rows significantly.
df2 = df.loc[
    (df['fp'] == 'FY') & 
    (df['fy'] == 2023) & 
    (df['form'] == '10-K')
]

# we find all facts which contain 'investments'
lst = [s for s in sorted(list(set(df2['fact'].tolist())))
       if 'investments' in s.lower()]

Formulation of Task#


In order to obtain the balance sheet as reported on EDGAR, using data from EDGAR API, we must do this:


    

  • find the facts that correspond to the fields appearing on the balance sheet
    • 

  • read and collate the (last) values that correspond to these facts
    • 



This is what we will do in the following.






Mapping of Fields and Facts#


We have earlier shown the map between the field name Short-term Investments and the fact OtherShortTermInvestments. Painstakingly repeating what we have done for the other field names, we obtain the following map:






# Put these facts into a Python list by the same name
facts = [
    'CashAndCashEquivalentsAtCarryingValue',
    'OtherShortTermInvestments',
    'CashCashEquivalentsAndShortTermInvestments',
    'MarketableSecurities',
    'AccountsReceivableNetCurrent',
    'InventoryNet',
    'PrepaidExpenseAndOtherAssetsCurrent',
    'AssetsCurrent',
    'EquityMethodInvestments',
    'OtherInvestments',
    'OtherAssetsNoncurrent',

    'PropertyPlantAndEquipmentNet',

    'OtherIntangibleAssetsNet',
    'Assets',

    'NotesAndLoansPayable',

# Here, we try to output the balance sheet for 2022 and 2023 combined.
# It turns out that this is complicated by the discovery that
# the fact "NotesAndLoansPayable" from 2023 needs to be replaced 
# by "ShortTermBorrowings" for 2022.
facts[18] = "ShortTermBorrowings"
df2o = df.loc[
    (df['fp'] == 'FY') & 
    (df['fy'] == 2022) & 
    (df['form'] == '10-K')
]
df3o = df2o.loc[df2o['fact'].isin(facts)]\
           .drop_duplicates('fact', keep='last')
df4o = df3o[['fact', 'val']]
df4o.index = range(len(df4o))
df4o.at[30, 'fact'] = 'NotesAndLoansPayable'
facts[18] = 'NotesAndLoansPayable'
df4o = df4o.set_index('fact').sort_index().loc[facts]

# Output to csv
import pandas as pd
df5 = pd.concat([df4, df4o], axis=1)
df5.to_csv('ko_bs_2023-2022_edgartools.csv')















Obtaining Notes to Financial Statements#






# Get the html of the latest 10-K filing
filings = get_filings(form="10-K")
filing = filings[0]

# This html file may be opened at the filing may be viewed
html = filing.html()
with open("KO_10k.html", "w") as f:
    f.write(html)

investors may not be able to transfer or otherwise dispose of our shares\nof common stock, par value $0.001 (Common Stock) at the desired time and prices, or at all.\nWe may have difficulty sourcing investment opportunities.\nWe generally will not control the business operations of our portfolio companies.\nWe may not be able to dispose of our interests in our portfolio companies.\nWe may borrow other funds, accounts and clients.\nRisks Related to BDCs\nChanges in laws or regulations governing our operations may adversely affect our business.\nWe are subject to limited restrictions with respect to our assets.\nFailure to maintain our status as a BDC would reduce our operating flexibility.\nRisks Related to Our Investments\nOur investments in portfolio companies may be risky, and we could lose all or part of our investments.\nInvesting in middle market companies involves a number of significant risks.\nWe may be exposed to distressed lending risks.\nWe may suffer a loss if a portfolio company defaults on a loan.\nRisks Related to the Private Placement of Common Stock\nOur stockholders (Stockholders) will be obligated to fund drawdowns.\nStockholders who default on their Capital Commitment (as defined below) will be subject to significant adverse\nconsequences.\nCertain Stockholders may have to comply with Exchange Act filing requirements.\nTable of Contents\nRisks BUSINESS\nThe\nCompany \x97 26North BDC, Inc.\nThe Company, a Maryland corporation, is an externally managed,\nnon-diversified, closed-end management investment company that has elected to be regulated as a BDC under the Investment Company Act of 1940, as amended (the 1940\nAct). The Adviser, a Delaware limited partnership and subsidiary of 26North Partners LP, serves as our investment adviser and is responsible for portfolio and risk management of the Company. Subject to the overall supervision of our board of\ndirectors (the Board of Directors), the Adviser manages our day-to-day operations and provides investment advisory and management services to us. We also\nintend to elect to be treated, and intend to qualify annually thereafter, as a RIC under Subchapter M of the Code, for U.S. federal income tax purposes. As a BDC and a RIC, we will be required to comply with certain regulatory requirements. See\nItem 1. Business \x97 Regulation as a Business Development Company and Item 1. Business \x97 Certain U.S. Federal Income Tax Considerations.\nOur investment objective is to generate current income and, to a lesser extent, capital appreciation. We invest primarily in directly originated senior\nsecured loans to middle market companies domiciled in the United States. The Companys portfolio will consist primarily of direct originations of (i)\xa0first lien senior secured debt and unitranche debt (including last out portions of such\nloans) and, to a lesser extent, (ii)\xa0second lien senior secured debt and unsecured debt, including mezzanine debt. In connection with its debt investments, the Company is permitted to receive equity warrants or make select equity co-investments. We generally consider middle market companies to consist of companies with between $25\xa0million and $100\xa0million of annual earnings before interest expense, income tax expense, depreciation\nand amortization (EBITDA), although the Company may from time to time invest in larger or smaller companies.\nAlthough we invest primarily in\nmiddle market companies domiciled in the United States, we also may from time to time invest, to a lesser extent, in companies domiciled outside of the United States (subject to compliance with BDC requirements to invest at least 70% of our assets\nin United States companies).\nTo achieve our investment objective, we will leverage the experience, talent and extensive network of relationships of\n26Norths investment personnel (the Investment Team) to source and evaluate opportunities. There are no assurances that we will achieve our investment objective.\nWe currently intend to list our shares of Common Stock on a national securities exchange (an Exchange Listing) as determined by the Adviser in its\nsole discretion within seven years of the Reorganization (as defined below), which was effected on October\xa02, 2023, subject to market conditions. We also may pursue one or more liquidity events within seven years of the Reorganization, as\ndetermined by the Adviser in its sole discretion, including: (i)\xa0to commence a share repurchase program in which we repurchase a portion of our Common Stock on a periodic basis at a purchase price equal to our net asset value per share;\n(ii)\xa0a merger or other transaction in which Stockholders receive cash or shares of a listed company; (iii)\xa0a sale of all or substantially all of our assets either on a complete portfolio basis or individually to an unaffiliated third party\nor an affiliate followed by liquidation; and/or (iv)\xa0an orderly wind down and/or liquidation (including an Exchange Listing, each, a Liquidity Event). There can be no assurance that any Liquidity Event will occur. In light of the\nilliquid nature of our portfolio, a sale of assets by the Company to an affiliate likely would be predicated upon the Company obtaining exemptive and/or no-action relief from the SEC; however, there can be no\nassurance that the Company would be able to obtain such exemptive and/or no-action relief from the SEC.\nTable of Contents\nIf we do not consummate any Liquidity Event within seven years of the Reorganization, we may determine to\n(but shall not be obligated to) offer Stockholders the option to restructure their investment by either (i)\xa0exchanging all or a portion of their shares of Common Stock for an interest in a vehicle that would seek to liquidate and distribute to\nits shareholders the proceeds of its investments over time as such vehicle is liquidated in an orderly manner (a Liquidating Vehicle), pursuant to which any unfunded Capital Commitments (as defined below) of such Stockholders in the\nCompany would be extinguished, and/or (ii)\xa0exchanging their shares of Common Stock for shares in a newly formed entity that will elect to be treated as a BDC under the 1940 Act and a RIC under Subchapter M of the Code, and which may, among\nother things, seek to publicly list its shares. Any such restructuring may be predicated upon the Company obtaining an exemptive order from the SEC, as well as applicable approvals from the Board of Directors and/or Stockholders.\nlock-up agreement with the underwriters of any public offering of the Common Stock conducted in connection with an\nExchange Listing or otherwise. In addition, during the\nLock-Up Period (as described below), Stockholders will be restricted from: (1)\xa0offering, pledging, selling, contracting to sell, selling any option\nor contract to purchase, purchasing any option or contract to sell, granting any option, right or warrant to purchase or otherwise transferring or disposing of, directly or indirectly, any shares of Common Stock or securities convertible into or\nexchangeable or exercisable for any shares of Common Stock, or publicly disclosing the intention to make any offer, sale, pledge or disposition, (2)\xa0entering into any swap or other arrangement that transfers all or a portion of the economic\nconsequences associated with the ownership of Common Stock or any such other securities (regardless of whether any of these transactions are to be settled by the delivery of Common Stock or such other securities, in cash or otherwise), or\n(3)\xa0if applicable, making any demand for or exercising any right with respect to the registration of any shares of Common Stock or any security convertible into or exercisable or exchangeable for Common Stock. The\nLock-Up Period is 90 days after the date of an Exchange Listing for all shares of Common Stock held by a Stockholder, 180 days after the date of an Exchange Listing for\ntwo-thirds of the shares of Common Stock held by a Stockholder, and 270 days after the date of an Exchange Listing for\none-third of the shares of Common Stock held by a\nStockholder. The\nlock-up will apply to all shares of Common Stock acquired prior to an Exchange Listing but will not apply to any shares acquired in open market transactions or acquired pursuant to the\ndividend reinvestment plan after the date of an Exchange Listing.\nThe Companys administrative and executive offices are located at 600 Madison\nAvenue, 26th Floor, New York, NY 10022.\nFormation Transactions\nThe Company was formed on October\xa013, 2022 as a corporation under the laws of the State of Maryland.\nWe have conducted, and anticipate that we will continue to conduct, private offerings of our shares of Common Stock (each, a Private Offering), in\nthe United States to accredited investors within the meaning of Regulation D under the Securities Act of 1933, as amended (1933 Act), and outside the United States in accordance with Regulation S or Regulation D under the\n1933 Act, in reliance on exemptions from the registration requirements of the 1933 Act. At each closing of the current Private Offering, each investor will make a capital commitment (a Capital Commitment) to purchase shares of our Common\nStock pursuant to a subscription agreement entered into with the Company (each a Subscription Agreement). Investors are required to fund drawdowns to purchase shares of Common Stock up to the amount of their respective Capital Commitment\non an as-needed basis each time we deliver a drawdown notice. Business\x97The Private Offering.\nOn October\xa02, 2023 (the Exchange Date), prior to the commencement of the Companys operations, 26N Direct Lending Fund LP, a private\nfund that was not registered under the 1940 Act or the Exchange Act (the\nTable of Contents\nPrivate Fund), was reorganized with and into the Company (the Reorganization). The Board of Directors considered, deemed to be in the Companys best interest and\napproved the Agreement and Plan of Exchange and Reorganization, dated October\xa02, 2023, in order to effect the Reorganization. The Reorganization was comprised of the conveyance, assignment, transfer and delivery by 26N Direct Lending Fund\n(Blocker), LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (the Blocker), and the Private Fund to the Company of the right, title and interest in and to the capital commitments of the members of the Blocker to the Blocker and the capital\ncommitments of the limited partners of the Private Fund to the Private Fund (excluding, for the avoidance of doubt, the capital commitment made by the Blocker to the Private Fund), respectively, as of the Exchange Date. Prior to the Reorganization,\nthe Adviser assumed the Private Funds known liabilities, which the Company agreed to reimburse to the Adviser under the Expense Support Agreement (defined below), provided that the Company commenced operations prior to such reimbursement.\n26North\n26North commenced operations in 2022 with its\nprincipal place of business in New York, NY and is building an integrated, multi-asset class investment platform. 26North seeks to provide asset management services to its clients related to a variety of investment strategies\x97currently, Private\nEquity, Direct Lending, and Reinsurance\xa0& Insurance Asset Management. As of December\xa031, 2023, 26North has approximately $15.0\xa0billion in assets under management and a team of more than 95 professionals, comprised of a combination\nof full-time employees, operating partners and senior advisors.1\n26North was founded by Josh Harris\n(the Founder), who has over 30 years of experience in asset management. 26North expects to benefit from the industry experience and relationships of Josh Harris and other senior investment professionals. 26North provides, or will\nprovide, investment advisory services to pooled investment vehicles (the 26North Funds), institutional clients via separately managed accounts (the Separate Accounts) and insurance companies, reinsurance companies and other\ninsurance-related clients (the Insurance Company Clients). 26North also provides investment management services to HRS Management, LLC (the Family Office), Josh Harris multi-faceted, single-family office with a\nlong-dated capital base and investments across multiple asset classes. 26North also expects to provide investment management services to other large-scale family offices (the Third Party Family Offices and, together with the Family\nOffice, the Family Office Clients). The 26North Funds, Separate Accounts, Insurance Company Clients and the Family Office Clients are referred to collectively herein as the Clients.\n26North tailors, and in the future will tailor, its advisory services to the specific investment objectives of each existing and future Client pursuant to the\ninvestment guidelines and restrictions set forth in each Clients confidential private placement memorandum, offering memorandum, prospectus, limited partnership agreement, advisory agreement, management agreement and other governing documents,\nas applicable, which will generally be established at the time of entry into the applicable advisory relationship.\n1\tOperating partners and senior advisors are independent consultants and not employees of 26North. The Adviser acts as the Companys investment adviser\npursuant to an investment advisory agreement with the Company (the Investment Advisory Agreement), and is a registered investment adviser with the SEC under the Investment Advisers Act of 1940, as amended (the Advisers Act).\nSubject to the overall supervision of the Board of Directors, the Adviser is responsible for managing our business and activities, including sourcing investment opportunities, conducting research, performing diligence on potential investments,\nstructuring our investments and monitoring our portfolio companies on an ongoing basis through a team of investment professionals. The Adviser is located at 600 Madison Avenue, 26th Floor, New\nYork, NY 10022. The Adviser is a subsidiary of 26North Partners LP. 26North Partners LP is controlled by Josh Harris, our Founder.\nThe Advisers\nDirect Lending investment strategy is led by an Investment Committee (the Investment Committee) comprised of Josh Harris, Brendan McGovern, Mike Mastropaolo, Jordan Walter, David Yu and Mark Weinberg. The primary responsibility for the day-to-day implementation of management of the Companys investment portfolio is Brendan McGovern (the Portfolio Manager).\nIn implementing our investment strategy, the Portfolio Manager will have access to the experience and expertise of the Investment Team and the Investment\nCommittee.\nThe Adviser and its affiliates may provide management or investment services to others whose objectives overlap with ours. The Adviser may\nface conflicts in the allocation of investment opportunities to us and others. To address these conflicts, the Adviser has put in place an investment allocation policy that seeks to ensure fair and equitable allocation of investment opportunities\nover time and address the co-investment restrictions set forth under the 1940 Act. Risk Factors \x97 Risks Related to the Adviser and its Affiliates \x97 The Adviser or its affiliates\nmay have incentives to favor their respective other funds, accounts and clients over us, which may result in conflicts of interest that could be adverse to us and our investment opportunities and harmful to us.\nAdministrator\n26North Direct Lending Administration LLC\nserves as our Administrator. The principal executive office of the Administrator is located at 600 Madison Avenue, 26th Floor, New York, NY 10022. The Administrator provides the administrative\nservices necessary for us to operate pursuant to an administration agreement between us and the Administrator (the Administration Agreement). See Item 1. Business\x97Administration Agreement below for a discussion of\nthe fees and expenses we are required to reimburse to the Administrator.\nThe Administrator, on behalf of us and at our expense, may retain one or more\nservice providers that may or may not also be affiliates of 26North to serve as sub-administrator, custodian, accounting agent, investor services agent, transfer agent or other service provider for us. Any\nfees we pay, or indemnification obligations we undertake, in respect of the administrator and those other service providers that are 26North affiliates, will be set at arms length and approved by the Independent Directors (as defined below).\nThe Administrator entered into a sub-administration agreement with SEI Global Services, Inc. (SEI) pursuant to which SEI will receive compensation for its services.\nThe Board of Directors\nOverall responsibility for the\nCompanys oversight rests with the Board of Directors. We have entered into the Investment Advisory Agreement with the Adviser, pursuant to which the Adviser manages the Company as described herein. The Board of Directors is responsible for\noverseeing the Adviser and other service providers in our operations in accordance with the provisions of the 1940 Act, the Companys Articles of Amendment and Restatement (the Charter) and Amended and Restated Bylaws (the\nBylaws) and applicable provisions of state and other laws. The Adviser will keep the Board of Directors well informed as to the Advisers activities on\nTable of Contents\nour behalf and our investment operations and provide the Board of Directors with additional information as the Board of Directors may, from time to time, request. The Board of Directors is\ncurrently composed of three (3)\xa0directors, two (2)\xa0of whom are directors who are not interested persons of the Company or the Adviser as defined in the 1940 Act (Independent Directors). The Board of Directors meets\nat regularly scheduled quarterly meetings each year. In addition, the Board of Directors may hold special in-person or telephonic meetings or informal conference calls to discuss specific matters that may\narise or require action between regular meetings. As described below, the Board of Directors has established an Audit Committee and a Nominating and Governance Committee, and may establish ad hoc committees or working groups from time to time, to\nassist the Board of Directors in fulfilling its oversight responsibilities.\nCompetition\nWe operate in a highly competitive market for investment opportunities. We compete for investments with various other investors, such as other public and\nprivate funds, other BDCs, commercial and investment banks, commercial finance companies and to the extent they provide an alternative form of financing, private equity funds, some of which may be our affiliates. Other 26North Funds may have\ninvestment objectives that overlap with ours, which may create competition for investment opportunities. Many competitors are substantially larger and have considerably greater financial, technical and marketing resources than we do. For example,\nsome competitors may have a lower cost of funds and access to funding sources that will not be available to us. In addition, some of our competitors may have higher risk tolerances or different risk assessments than we do, which could allow them to\nconsider a wider variety of investments and establish more relationships than us. Furthermore, many of our competitors are not subject to the regulatory restrictions that the 1940 Act and the Code impose on us. The competitive pressures could impair\nour business, financial condition, and results of operations. As a result of this competition, we may not be able to take advantage of attractive investment opportunities.\nInvestment Process Overview\nInvestment Process\nThe Adviser strives to leverage a streamlined and efficient investment process:\nDeal Sourcing and Initial Evaluation: Investment opportunity is identified and evaluated for viability\nprior to initiating a consensus buildout of initial views and risks.\nStaffing: Full deal team requested for continued evaluation of the prospective opportunity.\nInitial Diligence Presentation: Deal team focuses on key risks and investment thesis points and then\npresents a memo to the Investment Committee for screening. A detailed diligence roadmap and indicative terms are also sent to the company or sponsor at this stage.\nPrimary Diligence Presentation: The deal team works with the prospective investment to address the\nAdvisers needs and findings are presented to the Investment Committee, who then agree on a firm commitment.\nFinal Diligence Presentation: The deal team conducts remaining confirmatory diligence and presents to the\nInvestment Committee. At this stage legal, compliance and operations are all involved for final allocation and funding.\nDue\nDiligence Process\nAs the middle market loans in which we typically invest are exposed to loss of principal but have capped upside, the\nAdvisers due diligence process will focus on identifying risk in an effort to ensure that our investments are downside protected. In conducting diligence, the Adviser will utilize private equity style diligence, including a bottom-up, fundamental research approach to its potential investments. The Adviser expects to use varied and\nTable of Contents\nextensive sources of information to inform its view, leveraging the expertise of its personnel and legal counsel. In conducting due diligence, the Adviser seeks to leverage information provided\nby companies, financial sponsors and publicly available information, as well as information from relationships with former and current management teams, consultants, competitors and investment bankers.\nThe Advisers due diligence of a prospective portfolio company will typically include:\nreview of historical and prospective financial information, including audited financials, quality of earnings\nreports, and projection models, with a focus on understanding the degree to which a company can support its debt obligations in downside scenarios;\nreview of the capital structure of the company;\nanalysis of the business and industry in which the company operates, taking into consideration legal, regulatory\nand sector specific risks;\ninterviews with management, employees, customers and vendors of the potential portfolio company;\nreview of loan documents;\nrisk factors associated with environmental, social and governance (ESG) issues;\nbackground checks; and\nresearch relating to the portfolio companys management, industry, markets, products and services and\ncompetitors.\nThe Adviser expects to utilize attorneys, independent auditors and other third-party advisers to conduct additional due\ndiligence with respect to an investment prior to the closing of an investment where appropriate. Upon the completion of due diligence and a decision to proceed with an investment in a company, the team leading the investment presents the investment\nopportunity to the Investment Committee. The Investment Committee will determine whether to pursue the potential investment. All new investments are required to be reviewed by the Investment Committee.\nPortfolio Monitoring\nThe Adviser undertakes an\nongoing monitoring approach to portfolio management, which is designed to create a culture of risk management as outlined below:\nReal-time portfolio monitoring:\nActive engagement with portfolio companies.\nContinuous review of key performance metrics.\nSeek to identify themes and address underperformance early-on.\nReal-time regular reporting:\nFlash credit reports and extensive quarterly write-ups.\nPerformance tracking in information management system.\nOversight by Investment Committee.\nQuarterly robust valuations:\nIndependent process with experienced third-party valuation agents.\nIndependent oversight on individual marks.\n10\nTable of Contents\nMultiple layers of internal and external review.\nMonthly and ad hoc watchlist discussions:\nThorough assessments and extensive discussions with the Investment Committee.\nTake proactive action designed to address underperformance early-on.\nSourcing and Structuring of Investments\nOur approach to structuring direct lending loans involves us choosing the most appropriate variety of securities for each particular investment; and\nnegotiating the best and most favorable terms.\nInvestment Advisory Agreement\nGeneral\nThe description below of the Investment\nAdvisory Agreement is only a summary and is not necessarily complete. The description set forth below is qualified in its entirety by reference to the Investment Advisory Agreement attached as an exhibit to this Annual Report.\nUnder the terms of the Investment Advisory Agreement, the Adviser is responsible for the following:\nmanaging the investment and reinvestment of our assets in accordance with our investment objective, policies and\nrestrictions, the 1940 Act, the Advisers Act and all other applicable federal and state law, and our Charter and Bylaws;\ndetermining the composition of our portfolio, the nature and timing of the changes therein and the manner of\nimplementing such changes;\nidentifying, evaluating and negotiating the structure of the investments made by us (including by performing due\ndiligence on prospective portfolio companies);\nexecuting, closing, servicing and monitoring our investments;\ndetermining the securities and other assets that we will purchase, retain or sell; and\nproviding us with such other investment advisory, research and related services as we may, from time to time,\nreasonably require for the investment of our funds.\nThe Advisers services under the Investment Advisory Agreement are not\nexclusive, and it is free to furnish similar services to other entities so long as its services to us are not impaired.\nTerm\nUnless earlier terminated as described below, the Investment Advisory Agreement will continue in effect for an initial term of two years from the date it first\nbecame effective, and from year to year thereafter if approved annually by the Board of Directors or by the holders of a Majority of the Outstanding Shares of Common Stock (as defined below) and, in each case, a majority of the Independent\nDirectors.\nThe Investment Advisory Agreement will automatically terminate within the meaning of the 1940 Act and related SEC guidance and interpretations\nin the event of its assignment (as such term is defined for purposes of Section\xa015(a)(4) of the 1940 Act). In accordance with the 1940 Act, without payment of penalty, we may terminate the Investment Advisory Agreement with the\nAdviser upon 60 days written notice. The decision to terminate the agreement may be made by a majority of the Board of Directors or the Stockholders holding a Majority of the Outstanding Shares of Common Stock. Majority of the\nOutstanding Shares of Common Stock means the lesser of (1) 67% or more of the outstanding shares of Common Stock present at a meeting, if the\n11\nTable of Contents\nholders of more than 50% of the outstanding shares of Common Stock are present or represented by proxy or (2)\xa0a majority of outstanding shares of Common Stock. In addition, without payment\nof penalty, the Adviser may generally terminate the Investment Advisory Agreement upon 60 days written notice.\nCompensation of the Adviser\nWe will pay the Adviser an investment advisory fee for its services under the Investment Advisory Agreement consisting of two components: a\nManagement Fee (described below) and an Incentive Fee (described below). The cost of both the Management Fee and the Incentive Fee will ultimately be borne by the Stockholders.\nManagement Fee\nThe Management Fee is payable quarterly\nin arrears. The Management Fee is payable at an annual rate of 0.75% (1.00% in the event of an Exchange Listing (as defined below)) of the average value of our gross assets at the end of each of our two most recently completed calendar quarters. For\npurposes of calculating the Management Fee, gross assets means the total assets of the Company determined on a consolidated basis in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America\n(GAAP) , excluding cash and cash equivalents but including assets purchased with borrowed amounts.\nThe Management Fee for any partial quarter\nwill be appropriately prorated and adjusted for any share issuances or repurchases of our Common Stock during the relevant calendar quarter.\nIncentive\nFee\nWe will pay to the Adviser an Incentive Fee that will consist of two parts. The Investment Income Incentive Fee will be calculated and\npayable on a quarterly basis, in arrears, and will equal 10% (17.5% in the event of an Exchange Listing) of Pre-Incentive Fee Net Investment Income for the immediately preceding calendar quarter,\nsubject to a quarterly preferred return of 1.5% (i.e., 6.0% annualized), or Hurdle, measured on a quarterly basis and a catch-up feature.\nPre-Incentive Fee Net Investment Income means interest income, dividend income and any other income\n(including any accrued income that the Company has not yet received in cash and any other fees such as commitment, origination, structuring, diligence and consulting fees or other fees that the Company receives from portfolio companies) accrued\nduring the calendar quarter minus the Companys operating expenses accrued during the calendar quarter (including the Management Fee, administrative expenses and any interest expense and dividends paid on issued and outstanding preferred stock,\nbut excluding the Incentive Fee). These calculations shall be appropriately adjusted for any share issuances or repurchases during the quarter (based on the actual number of days elapsed relative to the total number of days in such calendar\nquarter).\nPre-Incentive Fee Net Investment Income for the immediately preceding calendar quarter, expressed as a\nrate of return on the value of our net assets at the beginning of the immediately preceding calendar quarter, will be compared to a Hurdle Amount equal to the product of (i)\xa0the Hurdle rate of 1.50% per quarter (6.0% annualized) and\n(ii)\xa0our net assets (defined as total assets less indebtedness and before taking into account any Incentive Fees payable during the period) at the beginning of the immediately preceding calendar quarter.\nWe will pay the Adviser an Investment Income Incentive Fee in each calendar quarter as follows:\nNo Investment Income Incentive Fee is payable to the Adviser in any calendar quarter in which the Pre-Incentive Fee Net Investment Income does not exceed the Hurdle Amount for such calendar quarter;\n100% of the Pre-Incentive Fee Net Investment Income with respect to that\nportion of such Pre-Incentive Fee Net Investment Income, if any, that exceeds the Hurdle Amount but is less than\n12\nTable of Contents\n\t1.6667% (1.8182% in the event of an Exchange Listing) for that calendar quarter is payable to the Adviser. We refer to this portion of our Pre-Incentive Fee Net Investment Income as the \x93catch-up\x94; and\n\n10% (17.5% in the event of an Exchange Listing) of the Companys\nPre-Incentive Fee Net Investment Income, if any, that exceeds 1.6667% (1.8182% following an Exchange Listing) in any calendar quarter is payable to the Adviser.\nBecause of the structure of the Investment Income Incentive Fee, it is possible that we may pay an Investment Income Incentive Fee in a calendar quarter in\nwhich we incur a loss. For example, if we receive Pre-Incentive Fee Net Investment Income in excess of the Hurdle rate, we will pay the applicable Investment Income Incentive Fee even if we have incurred a\nloss in that calendar quarter due to realized and unrealized capital losses. In addition, because the Hurdle Amount is calculated based on our net assets, decreases in our net assets due to realized or unrealized capital losses may increase the\nlikelihood that the Hurdle Amount is reached and therefore the likelihood of us paying an Incentive Fee in a given calendar quarter. In addition, if market interest rates rise, we may be able to invest our funds in debt instruments that provide for\na higher return, which would increase our Pre-Incentive Fee Net Investment Income and make it easier for the Adviser to surpass the fixed Hurdle rate and receive an incentive fee based on such net investment\nincome. Our net investment income used to calculate this component of the Incentive Fee is also included in the amount of our gross assets used to calculate the Management Fee because gross assets are total assets (including cash received) before\ndeducting liabilities (such as declared dividend payments).\nThe following is a graphical representation of the calculation of the income-related portion\nof the incentive fee prior to an Exchange Listing:\nThe following is a graphical representation of the calculation of the income-related portion of the incentive fee following\nan Exchange Listing:\nThe Capital Gains Incentive Fee will be an annual fee that will be determined and payable, in arrears, as of\nthe end of each calendar year (or upon termination of the Investment Advisory Agreement) in an amount equal to 10% (17.5% following an Exchange Listing) of realized capital gains, if any, determined on a cumulative basis from the commencement of the\nCompanys investment operations (based on the fair market value of each investment as of such date) through the end of such calendar year (or upon termination of the Investment Advisory Agreement), computed net of all realized capital losses\nand unrealized capital depreciation on a cumulative basis from the commencement of the Companys investment operations (based on the fair market value of each investment as of such date) through the end of such calendar year (or upon\ntermination of the Investment Advisory Agreement), less the aggregate amount of any previously paid Capital Gains Incentive Fees.\nWe will accrue, but\nwill not pay, a Capital Gains Incentive Fee with respect to unrealized appreciation because a Capital Gains Incentive Fee would be owed to the Adviser if we were to sell the relevant investment and realize a capital gain.\nThe fees that are payable under the Investment Advisory Agreement for any partial period will be appropriately prorated.\n13\nTable of Contents\nExamples of Quarterly Incentive Fee investment adviser of the Company, except to the extent specified in\nSection\xa036(b) of the 1940 Act concerning loss resulting from a breach of fiduciary duty (as the same is finally determined by We may pay the expenses incurred by the Indemnitee in defending an actual or threatened civil or criminal action in advance of the final disposition of such action, provided the Indemnitee agrees to repay those expenses if found by\nadjudication not to be entitled to indemnification. Notwithstanding the foregoing, in accordance with Section\xa017(i) of the 1940 Act, neither the Adviser nor any of its affiliates, directors, officers, members, employees, agents or\nrepresentatives may be protected against any liability to us or our investors to which it would otherwise be subject by reason of willful misfeasance, bad faith, gross negligence or reckless disregard of the duties involved in the conduct of its\noffice.\nBoard Approval of the Investment Advisory Agreement\nAt an in-person meeting held on September\xa06, 2023, the Board of Directors considered, deemed to be in our best\ninterest, and approved the Investment Advisory Agreement in accordance with applicable 1940 Act requirements, including any SEC exemptive relief, no-action or other guidance issued by the staff of the SEC. Any Expense Payment that\nthe Adviser commits to pay must be paid by the Adviser to us in any combination of cash or other immediately available funds no later than forty-five days after such commitment is made in writing, and/or offset against amounts due from us to the\nAdviser or its affiliates.\nFollowing any calendar quarter in which Available Operating Funds (as defined below) exceed the cumulative distributions\naccrued to our Stockholders based on distributions declared with respect to record dates occurring in such calendar quarter (the amount of such excess referred to as Excess Operating Funds), we will pay such Excess Operating Funds, or a\nportion thereof, to the Adviser until such time as all Expense Payments made by the Adviser to us within three years prior to the last business day of such calendar quarter have been reimbursed. Any payments required to be made by us under the\nExpense Support Agreement are referred to as a Reimbursement Payment. Available Operating Funds means the sum of (i)\xa0our net investment company taxable income (including net short-term capital gains reduced by net\nlong-term capital losses), (ii) our net capital gains (including the excess of net long-term capital gains over net short-term capital losses) and (iii)\xa0dividends and other distributions paid to us on account of investments in portfolio\ncompanies (to the extent such amounts listed in clause (iii)\xa0are not included under clauses (i)\xa0and (ii) above).\nThe amount of the\nReimbursement Payment for any calendar quarter will equal the lesser of (i)\xa0the Excess Operating Funds in such quarter and (ii)\xa0the aggregate amount of all Expense Payments made by the Adviser to us within three years prior to the last\nbusiness day of such calendar quarter that have not been previously reimbursed by us to the Adviser; provided that the Adviser may waive its right to receive all or a portion of any Reimbursement Payment in any particular calendar quarter, in which\ncase such waived amount will remain unreimbursed Expense Payments reimbursable in future quarters pursuant to the terms of the Expense Support Agreement.\nOur obligation to make a Reimbursement Payment will automatically become a liability on the last business day of the applicable calendar quarter, except to\nthe extent the Adviser has waived its right to receive such payment for the applicable quarter. The Reimbursement Payment for any calendar quarter will be paid by us to the Adviser in any combination of cash or other immediately available funds as\npromptly as possible following such calendar quarter and in no event later than forty-five days after the end of such calendar quarter.\nNo Reimbursement\nPayment for any applicable calendar quarter shall be made if: (1)\xa0the Effective Rate of Distributions Per Share declared by the Company at the time of such proposed Reimbursement Payment is less than the Effective Rate of Distributions Per\nShare at the time the Expense Payment was made to which such Reimbursement Payment relates, or (2)\xa0the Companys Operating Expense Ratio at the time of such proposed Reimbursement Payment is greater than the Operating Expense Ratio at the\ntime the Expense Payment was made to which such Reimbursement Payment relates. Effective Rate of Distributions Per Share means the annualized rate (based on a 365-day year) of regular cash\ndistributions per share exclusive of returns of capital and declared special dividends or special distributions, if any. The Operating Expense Ratio is calculated by dividing all of the Companys operating costs and expenses\nincurred, as determined in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles for investment companies, less organizational and offering expenses, base management and incentive fees owed to the Adviser, and interest expense, by the\nCompanys net assets.\nEither we or the Adviser may terminate the Expense Support Agreement at any time, with or without notice, without the payment\nof any penalty, provided that any Expense Payments that have not been reimbursed by us to the Adviser will remain our obligation following any such termination, subject to the terms of the Expense Support Agreement.\nTrademark License Agreement\nWe have entered into a\nTrademark License Agreement (the License Agreement) with 26North Partners LP, pursuant to which we have been granted a non-exclusive license to use the names 26N and\n26North. In addition, we will take advantage of the extended transition period provided in Section\xa07(a)(2)(B) of the 1933 Act for complying with new or revised\naccounting standards.\nDistribution Reinvestment Plan\nWe have adopted an opt out distribution reinvestment plan that provides for reinvestment of our distributions on behalf of our Stockholders, unless\na Stockholder elects to receive cash. As a result, if our Board of Directors authorizes, and we declare, a cash dividend or other distribution, then Stockholders who do not opt out of our distribution reinvestment plan will have their\ncash distributions automatically reinvested in additional shares of Common Stock, rather than receiving cash distributions. Investors can elect to opt out of our distribution reinvestment plan in their Subscription Agreements.\nThere will be no brokerage charges or other charges to Stockholders who participate in the distribution reinvestment plan. The plan administrators fees\nwill be paid by us.\nStockholders who receive distributions in the form of stock are generally subject to the same U.S. federal, state and local tax\nconsequences as are Stockholders who elect to receive their distributions in cash. However, since a participating Stockholders cash distributions will be reinvested, such Stockholder will not receive cash with which to pay any applicable taxes\non reinvested distributions. A Stockholders basis for determining gain or loss upon the sale of stock received in a distribution from us will generally be equal to the total dollar amount of the distribution payable to the Stockholder. Any\nstock received in a distribution will have a new holding period for tax purposes commencing on the day following the day on which the shares are credited to the U.S. Stockholders account.\nThe plan will be terminable by us upon notice in writing mailed to each Stockholder of record at least 30 days prior to any record date for the payment of any\ndistribution by us.\nEmployees\nWe do not currently\nhave any employees and do not expect to have any employees.
